\section{Conclusion}
\label{Conclusion}

We have two ways of analyzing the data depending on what we compare, and how we compare it.
For the first comparison we find sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis for the first, but not the second transition. For the second comparison we do not find sufficient evidence to reject drift in either transition. These results hold for the analysis where we lump forms to gather to make a comparison when we add noise to document dates.

Now, we might ask whether there is any reason to choose one way of analyzing the data over the other. Given that the second  transition is not a necessary consequence of the first transition, we might consider the following reasons for lumping forms together. Namely, if the second transition had not occurred, then the embracing form would have gone to completion. That is, the signature of selection in the first transition is obscured by the fact that the second transition takes place. We can correct for this by treating the post-verbal forms \emph{as if} they were embracing forms. The results for the second transition are the same regardless of the analysis. However, again, given that the second transition does not necessarily follow from the first, it seems reasonable to treat pre-verbal forms \emph{as if} they were embracing.

The difference between Jespersen's Cycle and \emph{do}-support is largely one of sample size. There are only 51 unique documents for the period covered by Jespersen's Cycle, whereas there are hundreds for the time period of \emph{do}-support. This is striking for two reasons. First, while we might think of negation as a very frequent phenomenon, we are still limited by historical records. There are just fewer tokens the further back in historical time we go. Second, the assumption of normally distributed increments, which underlies the Gaussian approximation to the diffusion process, becomes an issue. In those cases where the rescaled increments are not normally distributed, the non-parametric version of the FIT sometimes rejects the null hypothesis.  \cite{steinrucken-etal2014} propose a method that does not rely on the Gaussian approximation, but is more computationally tractable than simulating the original approximation to the diffusion process.



\section{Future Directions}

The evidence presented suggests how the cycle depends on both use and acquisition. However, it is far from a complete picture. First, an extensive analysis of the various forms of negation in the PPCME2 will be necessary, both for a more accurate estimate of the evidence for both respective grammars, as well as an overview of the details concerning the various forms of negative elements, including other NPIs, negative adverbs, and negative quantifiers. Second, the relevant grammatical description of the change presented here is quite simplified relative to the more articulated approach discussed in \cite{wallage2008}. Namely, he divides the change in negation into finer parts. $ne$ goes from having interpretable [$i$neg] to an uninterpretable [$u$neg] negative feature. Such an analysis could be incorporated into the learning model presented here and might possibly shed light on the loss of $ne$ and other subsequent changes such as the loss of negative concord. Finally, the analysis of the cycle in Middle 
English could benefit greatly from a comparative perspective. The cycle in French differs widely in terms of both the relevant timeline and the evidence available at the onset of the change. Data from the MCVF Corpus of Middle French \citep{mcvf} could offer an important counterpoint and testing ground for the models presented thus far.



%\include{Chapter3}
%\include{Conclusions}
\chapter{Conclusion}

Pragmatic competence shapes the input to language acquisition, language acquisition gives rise to grammatical competence, and grammatical competence determines the set of signals at the disposal of our pragmatic competence. The goal of this dissertation is to advance our understanding of the relationship between the two as repeated in Figure \ref{second}. By loosening the assumption of perfectly common interests between speakers and hearers, we can gain insight into how the use of linguistic signals changes over time, and how this impacts acquisition. By generalizing the Gricean program we have been able to situate Jespersen's Cycle at the intersection of both. Neither by itself can account for the trajectory of the cycle, but both taken together are mutually informing and revealing.

\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}[->,>=stealth',shorten >=1pt,auto,node distance=3cm]
  \node (A)      {grammar $n$};
  \node (B) [below right of=A]  {data $n$};
  \node (C) [above right of=B] {grammar $n+1$};
  \node (D) [below right of=C] {data $n+1$};
  \node (E) [above right of=D] {};
\path[->] (A)  edge node {} (B)
  (B) edge node {} (C)
  (C) edge node {} (D)
  (D) edge[dashed] node {} (E);
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}
\caption{The iterated process of language acquisition and use}
\label{second}
\end{figure}



